hands_on_practices.solution:
We start with the final gravitational potential energy of the ZAMS star:  
$$U_f=-\eta\,\frac{GM^2}{R_f}$$  
Since the initial potential energy is negligible,  
$$\Delta U=U_f-0=-\eta\,\frac{GM^2}{R_f}\,. $$  
By the Virial Theorem half of $-\Delta U$ is radiated:  
$$E_{\rm grav}=-\frac12\Delta U=\frac12\,\eta\,\frac{GM^2}{R_f}\,. $$  
The classical Kelvin–Helmholtz timescale is  
$$t_{\rm KH}=\frac{E_{\rm grav}}{\bar L}
=\frac{\frac12\,\eta\,GM^2/R_f}{\bar L}
=\frac{\eta\,GM^2}{2R_f\,\bar L}\,. $$  
The total deuterium fusion energy is  
$$E_D=X_D\,M\,q_D\,. $$  
Thus the actual PMS timescale including deuterium is  
$$t=\frac{E_{\rm grav}+E_D}{\bar L}\,. $$  
The extension factor is  
$$F=\frac{t}{t_{\rm KH}}
=\frac{E_{\rm grav}+E_D}{E_{\rm grav}}
=1+\frac{E_D}{E_{\rm grav}}
=1+\frac{X_D\,M\,q_D}{\frac12\,\eta\,GM^2/R_f}
=1+\frac{2\,X_D\,q_D\,R_f}{\eta\,G\,M}\,. $$
